The festival kicked off on Friday evening with visual performances and an augmented reality presentation from Pharaonic-era tombs; traditional folk dances, Tanoura and Folk Dance Group; old songs of Nazih Azar, the legendary singer from the 1970s; independent singer Ragaa El-Geddawy and performances by Hamza Namira. Film, extending across three screens, and photo exhibitions can be viewed over the weekend. “We wanted it to be a place for performers, fans and visitors to share their love for cinema, theatre, fashion and music,” stated Abdullah. Apart from cinema, theatre and music film lovers can view documentary, animation and experimental sub-genres at the festival.
